# Chapter 15 — Networking Protocols
### (Cybersecurity / Ethical Hacking Perspective)

Protocols are the "rules of conversation" between systems. Nearly every practical hack targets a **specific protocol's weakness** — this chapter is one of the most exploit-relevant in the entire course.

---

## 1. Web & Application Protocols

| Protocol | Port | Function | Security Relevance |
|---|---|---|---|
| **HTTP** | 80 | Web traffic, unencrypted | All data sent in plaintext — sniffable, MITM-able |
| **HTTPS** | 443 | Encrypted web traffic (TLS/SSL) | Standard for secure web; still vulnerable to SSL stripping, weak cipher configs, cert issues |
| **FTP** | 20/21 | File transfer | **Plaintext credentials and data** — one of the most commonly flagged insecure protocols in pentests |
| **SFTP/FTPS** | 22/990 | Secure file transfer | Encrypted alternatives to FTP |
| **SMTP** | 25 | Email sending | Target of email spoofing (lacks built-in sender verification without SPF/DKIM/DMARC) |
| **POP3/IMAP** | 110/143 | Email retrieval | Plaintext versions expose credentials; use POP3S/IMAPS (995/993) instead |

---

## 2. Remote Access Protocols

| Protocol | Port | Function | Security Relevance |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Telnet** | 23 | Remote CLI access | **Completely plaintext** — credentials and commands fully visible to sniffing; should never be used today |
| **SSH** | 22 | Encrypted remote CLI access | Secure replacement for Telnet; still a top brute-force target (weak passwords, default creds) |
| **RDP** | 3389 | Remote desktop (Windows) | One of the **most commonly exploited/brute-forced services** exposed to the Internet — top initial access vector in ransomware incidents |
| **VNC** | 5900 | Remote desktop (cross-platform) | Often runs with weak/no authentication by default |

---

## 3. Name Resolution & Configuration Protocols

| Protocol | Port | Function | Security Relevance |
|---|---|---|---|
| **DNS** | 53 | Domain name resolution | Target of DNS spoofing/poisoning, DNS tunneling (data exfiltration/C2 channel), DNS amplification DDoS |
| **DHCP** | 67/68 | Automatic IP assignment | Target of rogue DHCP servers, DHCP starvation attacks |
| **NTP** | 123 | Time synchronization | Target of NTP amplification DDoS attacks |

---

## 4. File Sharing & Management Protocols

| Protocol | Port | Function | Security Relevance |
|---|---|---|---|
| **SMB (Server Message Block)** | 445 | Windows file/printer sharing | Historically massive attack surface — **EternalBlue (WannaCry, NotPetya)** exploited SMBv1 |
| **NFS** | 2049 | Unix/Linux file sharing | Misconfigurations can expose file systems without authentication |
| **SNMP** | 161/162 | Network device monitoring/management | Default/weak "community strings" (essentially passwords) are a common misconfiguration exploited for device takeover/info disclosure |

---

## 5. Security-Specific Protocols

| Protocol | Function | Security Relevance |
|---|---|---|
| **TLS/SSL** | Encrypts application-layer traffic | Foundation of HTTPS; weaknesses (old versions, weak ciphers) are actively tested in security assessments |
| **IPSec** | Encrypts traffic at the network layer (used in VPNs) | Core of many site-to-site VPN implementations |
| **Kerberos** | Authentication protocol (used heavily in Windows/Active Directory) | Target of "Kerberoasting" and "Golden/Silver Ticket" attacks — critical in AD penetration testing |
| **RADIUS/TACACS+** | Centralized authentication for network devices | Misconfiguration can allow authentication bypass |

---

## 6. Protocol-to-Attack Quick Reference

| Insecure Protocol | Why It's Dangerous |
|---|---|
| Telnet | Plaintext everything |
| FTP | Plaintext credentials/data |
| HTTP | Plaintext web traffic |
| SMBv1 | EternalBlue and related exploits |
| SNMP (v1/v2) | Weak default community strings, no encryption |

> **Golden rule for a pentester:** Any protocol found running that transmits data **in plaintext** is an automatic finding in a security assessment — this is one of the fastest, highest-value observations you can make when scanning a network (Nmap service detection reveals this instantly).

---

## 7. Why This Matters for Ethical Hacking

- **Service enumeration** (Nmap `-sV`) identifies exactly which protocols/services are running — this chapter is the "menu" of what you're looking for.
- **Most real-world breaches** trace back to exploitation of a specific insecure or misconfigured protocol (RDP brute-force, SMB exploitation, weak SNMP strings).
- **Protocol knowledge directly maps to exploit selection** in tools like Metasploit — knowing the protocol tells you which module/exploit category to consider.

---

## Quick Revision Points
- Plaintext protocols (Telnet, FTP, HTTP, SNMPv1/v2) are automatic security findings — replace with encrypted equivalents (SSH, SFTP, HTTPS, SNMPv3).
- RDP and SMB are two of the most commonly exploited remote access/file-sharing protocols in real-world ransomware attacks.
- DNS is abused for spoofing, poisoning, tunneling (data exfil), and amplification DDoS.
- Kerberos (Active Directory) has its own dedicated attack class (Kerberoasting, Golden/Silver Ticket) — critical for enterprise pentesting.
- Protocol enumeration is one of the very first and most valuable steps in any penetration test.

